  <h2 id="common-objects-inches">Common Objects Measured in Inches</h2>
  <p>Knowing typical inch measurements helps you estimate sizes and verify your ruler's calibration. Here are reference objects you encounter regularly.</p>
  <h3>US letter paper</h3>
  <p>A standard sheet of US letter paper measures 8.5 inches by 11 inches. This is the most common reference object for inch-based calibration. If you place a sheet of letter paper against your screen, it should measure exactly 8.5 inches wide. This is a quick way to verify your ruler's accuracy before important measurements.</p>
  <h3>Monitor and TV screen sizes</h3>
  <p>Screen sizes are always quoted diagonally in inches: 24-inch monitor, 55-inch TV, 6.1-inch phone display. The actual width of a 24-inch 16:9 monitor is about 20.9 inches, and the height is about 11.8 inches. A 55-inch TV measures roughly 47.9 inches wide and 27.0 inches tall. RulerKit's inch ruler can help you verify these dimensions if you want to check whether a TV stand or monitor arm will fit your space.</p>
  <h3>Hardware and construction</h3>
  <p>The construction industry in the US uses inches and feet almost exclusively. Standard measurements include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>2x4 lumber: actually 1.5 inches by 3.5 inches (nominal vs. actual dimension)</li>
    <li>Plywood thickness: 1/4 inch (0.25"), 3/8 inch (0.375"), 1/2 inch (0.5"), 3/4 inch (0.75")</li>
    <li>Drywall screws: typically 1-5/8 inches or 2 inches long</li>
    <li>Nail sizes: measured in "penny" (d) with common sizes like 8d (2.5 inches) and 16d (3.5 inches)</li>
    <li>Pipe diameter: 1/2 inch, 3/4 inch, 1 inch (nominal inside diameter)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Having these references at hand makes it easy to spot-check your ruler and confirm that your measurements are in the right ballpark before cutting or purchasing materials.</p>

  <h2 id="calibrating-for-inches">How to Calibrate for Inch Measurements</h2>
  <p>Calibration for inch measurements works exactly the same way as for centimeters. The unit you measure in does not affect the calibration process &mdash; you are simply telling the ruler the physical dimensions of your screen.</p>
  <p>To calibrate specifically for inch-based work: use a US letter sheet of paper (8.5 inches wide) as your reference object. Place it flat against your screen and adjust the calibration slider until the on-screen ruler reads 8.5 inches at the paper's edge. This gives you a calibration that is optimized for inch readings and verified against a common reference.</p>
  <p>Alternatively, you can use a standard credit card (3.37 inches wide). While credit cards are metric in origin (85.6 mm), the inch equivalent is well-established. After calibrating, test your ruler against a few known objects: a letter sheet (8.5 inches), a standard pencil (about 7.5 inches), or a smartphone (about 6 inches for a typical large phone). If all three read close to their expected values, your calibration is solid.</p>
  <p>RulerKit saves your calibration in local storage, so you only need to do this once. The ruler remembers your setting and applies it to both inch and centimeter measurements on future visits.</p>

  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq space-y-4 not-prose">
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">How do I read 1/16 inch marks on an online ruler?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">The 1/16 inch marks are the shortest lines on the ruler. Between each inch mark there are 15 short lines. Count the number of lines past the last inch mark to get the numerator, and use 16 as the denominator. For 1/4 inch, count 4 lines (4/16 = 1/4). RulerKit shows the fraction as a digital readout so you can confirm your visual reading.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Should I use fractional inches or decimal inches for my project?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Use fractions for construction, woodworking, and hardware (where tools and materials use fractional sizes). Use decimals for engineering, 3D printing, and digital design (where software uses decimal inputs). RulerKit shows both formats simultaneously, so you always have the right reading.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Do I need to calibrate differently for inches vs. centimeters?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">No. Calibration is the same regardless of the unit you plan to use. The PPI value is unit-agnostic. Once calibrated, switch between inches, centimeters, and millimeters freely without recalibrating.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Why does my inch ruler show marks at different lengths?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">RulerKit draws longer marks for larger fractions to make reading easier. The 1-inch mark is the longest, followed by 1/2 inch, then 1/4 inch, then 1/8 inch, with 1/16 inch being the shortest. This visual hierarchy helps you read measurements quickly without counting every tick.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Can I measure in inches on a phone or tablet?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Yes, but accuracy depends on screen size. Phones have small screens with high PPI, making precise alignment harder. Tablets offer a better experience. For inch measurements, a desktop or laptop display is recommended for the best balance of screen space and accuracy.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
